Loki is the son of the giant Farbauti and Laufey. Though of giant blood, he lives among and is accepted by the Aesir as Odin's blood-brother, occupying a unique and ambiguous position within the Norse pantheon.

Loki is known as the god of trickery, chaos, and magic, possessing the ability to shape-shift into various animals such as a salmon, a mare, or a fly. His cunning often makes him both the cause of and the solution to the gods' troubles, giving him a deeply ambiguous character, at times helpful and at other times harmful. He fathers three fearsome beings, the wolf Fenrir, the serpent Jormungandr, and the goddess Hel, ruler of the realm of the dead, and once gave birth to the horse Sleipnir after transforming himself into a mare.

